  "text": "The majority of autochthonous microflora of traditional dairy products are lactic acid bacteria (LAB) and their variety is a result of the great number by different strains. Beside selection for their application as starter or adjunct cultures (Radulović et al., 2011) , their selection as a potential probiotic is relatively new. Probiotics have recently been defined as \"live microbes which transit the gastrointestinal tract and in doing so benefit the health of the consumer\" [CITATION_1] . They are capable of surviving the low pH in the stomach. Most probiotic bacteria belong to the Lactobacillus genera and Bifidobacterium strains (Prasad et al., 1998) .",
